002-distributed-data/03-doing-things-lat.body:
Doing things later
Escaping the request
So far, everything we've done in our request handlers has been synchronous. When we receive a response to a request, we know the operations associated with it have either completed or timed out.
We've seen, however, how database systems support asynchronous replication. Because replicating each save to every database replica is expensive and error-prone, the database just acknowledges the save has been written to a single machine, or to a quorum of machines. The caller then just trusts the database system to do its best to replicate the save to all replicas at some point.
In a similar vein, we can also consider doing some of the operations initiated by a request asynchronously. That way, part of the work isn't constrained by the request.
Code example
function myRequestHandler(request, response) {
  let [parameterA, parameterB] = extractParametersFromRequest(request);

  getSomePartialResult(parameterA)
    .then((partialResult) => {
      let processedPartialResult = someProcessing(partialResult);

     // Do things in parallel. Synchronous does not mean one thing at a time,
     // it just means waiting for their results before responding.
     return Promise.all([
        parallelSubOperationA(processedPartialResult),
        parallelSubOperationB(processedPartialResult, parameterB),
      ]);
    })
    .then(([parallelResultA, parallelResultB]) => {
      let combinedResult = combineParallelResultsSomehow(
        parallelResultA,
        parallelResultB,
      );

      doSomethingElse()
        .then((somethingElse) => {
          // Asynchronous!
          // ... do something with somethingElse, maybe...
        });

      response.respondWith(combinedResult);

      // Synchronicity ends _here_! Everything that we're not sure it has
      // finished at this point is asynchronous.
      // That includes also doSomethingElse(). We _initiated_ it before
      // responding, but we didn't wait for it to finish.

      doMoreStuff()
        .then(() => {
          // Also asynchronous!
        });
    });
};

Why delay things?
Knowing how to do something is easy. Knowing why to do something, and especially when to choose to do so as an alternative to other options, is usually the tricky part.
Async != later
Let's first clarify something: doing something asynchronous doesn't imply doing it later. It just means not waiting for it to be finished. But it may actually finish before we respond to the request, or at a later time; we (from the perspective of the request handler) don't care.
So "delay" is not really the word we should be using.
Decouple the client from a task's completion
To find out what exactly is the difference between sync and async, let's reverse the question. Why not do things asynchronously?
The answer boils down to simplicity. We could handle every request asynchronously. The response doesn't really need to include the result of the operations the request handler initiated; it could just confirm that they were initiated, and the client could eventually get the feedback in some other way.
But, in a request-response pattern of communication, we usually want the response to include some result-like information beyond just "OK, I initiated a series of operations that will finish at some point". If we do this, then the client is forced to retrieve the results of such operations from somewhere else.
So doing things synchronously is a reasonable default strategy if we think the client will be interested in an informative result. (Even if this result is just that sub-operations finished, successfully or not! Which, as we've seen, tells the client whether it should retry the operation.)
But doing things synchronously imposes something on the client: the client also needs to wait. In effect, we tightly couple the client process's lifetime with those of all the synchronous operations it performs. The client can't make progress until the request is responded, even if it's not really interested in the result of the operation.
Doing things asynchronously is more complex. We could say that synchronicity is a layer of simplicity sugar built on top of an event-based asynchronous mess.
But it also doesn't force the participants in a request's lifetime (that is, the client and the server that handles the request) into waiting for all consequences of a request.
OK, so we've transformed the question into: why and when should we choose the complex decoupling of async over the convenient coupling of sync?
Optimize differently for different workloads
A common use case is to decouple different kinds of workloads.
By keeping machines specialized in one kind of task, we can optimize it, and the configuration around it, for performing that task.
A server thet receives requests from an arbitrary number of clients, such as an Internet-facing backend, should be specialized in serving requests. This is challenging enough on itself. If we keep request handling lightweight, we make the job of the backend easier.
Not having to wait for the tasks it initiates is a net gain for the backend: it means it can finish handling a request sooner, which frees the resources spent in it sooner.
Distributing jobs among workers
In the end, though, somebody needs to perform the tasks that the request is meant to initiate. How can we do that? We can use the job queue pattern.
In a job queue, we have the following components:

The job represents the task to be performed.
The worker is a process that performs a job.
The queue, where jobs wait to be performed.
The processes that put jobs in the queue, usually  request handlers.
The dispatcher is a process that continuously takes jobs from the queue and assigns them to workers, ensuring that the amount of workers at any given time is bounded. It is usually implemented as some amount of consumer processes that continuously attempt to take a job from the queue, and, if there is one, performs it, thus becoming a worker.


graph TD
  r1[request] --> queue
  r2[request] --> queue
  r3[request] --> queue
  r4[request] --> queue
  r5[request] --> queue
  r6[request] --> queue
  r7[...] --> queue
  queue --> dispatcher
  dispatcher --> w1[worker]
  dispatcher --> w2[worker]
  dispatcher --> w3[worker]
  dispatcher --> w4[worker]


This has the following properties:

The amount of workers performing jobs is bounded by some number.
The amount of active request handlers is independent of the amount of workers.
The queue:
Tends to grow as there are more requests.
Tends to shrink as there are more consumers.
Tends to shrink as workers are faster.


The latency (time from request to completion) of a job is proportional to the queue length.

The challenge, then, becomes preventing the queue from filling up.
Code example
// jobQueue is a queue in which we will put functions that, when called, do
// some job.
let jobQueue = [];

// consumeFromQueue takes a job from jobQueue, starts it, and when it finishes,
// starts again. Note that it only performs a job at a time.
function consumeFromQueue() {
  const startJob = jobQueue.shift(); // Dequeue first job.

  if (startJob !== undefined) {
    // If there is a job, do it. This then becomes a worker process.
    startJob()
      .then(() => consumeFromQueue()); // Consume again!
  } else {
    // If there isn't a job, try again asynchronously; next time there might be.
    setTimeout(consumeFromQueue, 0);
  }
}

// Start a _fixed_ number of consumers. This means we'll have a maximum of
// numConsumers jobs underway at any time. This way, we make sure we don't
// devote too many resources to performing the jobs. The only thing that will
// grow proportionally to the amount of jobs is the length of jobQueue, and the
// time it takes for jobs to be started since they're added by the request
// handler.
for (let i = 0; i  {
    return doSlowThing(parameters);
  });

  response.respondWith(okOrSomethingLikeThat);
}

Move latency to the background
This is a common scenario which is related to the previous one.
Maybe we're not really worried about the resources an operation may consume, but for some reason or another the latency of the operation may increase.
If we do the operation synchronously, then the client is affected by this latency increase. But if we do it asynchronously, someone is affected by this latency, but not the client, or not directly, at least. Thus, we move this latency to the background.
Decouple backends from the tasks to be performed
What if the backend doesn't know everything that needs to happen with a request?
This is a matter of separation of concerns that has more to do with event-based systems than with asynchronicity.
Event-based system
In an event-based system we find three components:

The events, pieces of data to be transmitted.
The emitters, processes that emit events.
The listeners, processes to be activated or created when an event is emitted.
The dispatcher, the procedure that, whenever an event is emitted, activates or creates listeners and let them access to the event data.

The advantage of event-based systems is that processes don't need to know about every consequence of a request. When something happens, you can do part of the associated work and then emit an event so that others can do other parts of the work you don't even know about. Doing more things then becomes a matter of adding more listeners to the event, without even touching the emitter.
Events and async
In theory, the dispatcher can be synchronous: when an event is emitted, the dispatch activates each listener, waits for all of them to finish, and only then the emitter can continue.
But it's more usual that the dispatcher is asynchronous. The emitter emits the event and immediately continues with its work.
Event-based systems and async are a good match, because, since the emitter doesn't know which kind of work the listeners will be performing with the event, it's also not interested in their results, since it doesn't even know which kind of results they might be.
An interesting use case for synchronous dispatchers is to notify clients of partial failure in the crash+retry approach to robust systems we've studied, but it's not really usual.
Keeping things causal
Asynchronicity makes it easier to fall into race conditions.
Recall that a race condition occurs when there's a mismatch between our expectations about how two events can affect each other and the reality. (Here, an event just means something happening.)
Whenever an event happens after another in the same process, there's a chance they're causally related, ie. that the first one affected the second one somehow. If this causality does exist, and we lose track of it, then that's a bug waiting to bite you.
Asynchronicity leads itself to race conditions.


We can keep order in the same way TCP does: by numbering the on the emitter side, so the order can be reconstructed on the listener side.
From sync to async and back to sync again
We said before that we can build synchronous systems on top of asynchronous systems. How so?
If the async operation emits an event when it's done, the initiator of the operation can first set a listener for such event.
Code example
function doAsynchronously(parameter) {
  doSomethingWithParameter(parameter)
    .then((result) => {
      emit('gotResult', result);
    });
}

on('gotResult', (result) => {
  doSomethingWithResult(result);
});

doAsynchronously(42);

// This looks kind of silly in JavaScript, but imagine the event dispatcher, the
// caller of doAsynchronously and the performer of doSomethingWithParameter are
// all on separate machines.

Clients won't retry async operations
We've seen how letting a single end client retry an operation when it times out or any level of the request handling either times out or crashes.
But if a client isn't waiting for acknowledgment of an operation, it's also not setting a timeout for it. It won't know if it succeeded or failed, so it can't retry it.
If you care that an async operation eventually succeeds, you need to set another kind of monitoring process that retries the operation.
A database for requests
We've seen how user-level clients, such as browsers or phones, can't be trusted to retry failed operations. So how can we put in charge of reliably retrying instead?
If you can't afford to get stuck in partial failure, then the very first thing you need to do is to store the request in a persistent database.
This ensures that, if the process crashes afterwards, we don't forget that, since the user's client might have forgotten already (remember: it can't be trusted; state on it is not durable). Then, another process can take over retrying the request by reading this database.
A kind of database that does all this for you is a message queue, also called message broker.
Async message brokers
Message brokers are typically async: the process of publishing a message is decoupled from the process of delivering it to consumers.
This means that they cannot propagate delivery errors to publishers, since the publishers don't wait for delivery.
There's no exactly-once
A message queue can ensure that a message will be delivered to consumers:

At least once.
At most once.

We typically would prefer exactly-once delivery, but that's not possible: once delivered, we don't know if the consumer has seen it or processed it unless it tells us, so we either wait for confirmation and re-deliver if we don't get it (at-least-once) or don't wait for confirmation and risk losing the message (at-most-once, also called fire-and-forget).
By making message processing idempotent, at-least-once is guaranteed to have the same effects as exactly-once. Yes, this is nothing new.
Message queues typically guarantee at-least-once delivery. They keep messages stored durable until they have confirmation that they can safely delete them. If they don't get such confirmation, they retry the delivery until they do.
Handling a message = handling a request
For all intents and purposes, handling a message delivery from an at-least-once message queue is the same as serving a request from a client. The message queue is making a request to you, and is expecting an acknowledgment back. You can follow the same let-it-crash strategy we've discussed in past chapters.
Message queues typically don't guarantee ordering
Some of them guarantee order inside a topic or channel, but not if events come from different channels.
You typically need to guarantee order yourself to avoid race conditions. If you get an event with a different serial number than you expected, then you just reject it, and let the message queue deliver it again at some later time; maybe at that time you will have processed all previous messages in the right order, and can then process this one.

102-appendix-good-practices/01-general-p.body:
General Good Practices
In medicine, there are some good practices followed by doctors to heal their patients. Some of them are specific to the discipline. For example, in surgery they use to apply anaesthesia and monitor the patient. There are some other good practices that are non-specific to any discipline. Washing the doctor hands or work in a clean environment are some examples.
In software, there are also some general good practices that can be applied to the art of programming. We will discuss some of them along this section.
Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY)
Writing the same piece of code in several places is not a good idea. Let's see an example:
class AuthService {
  login(username, password) {
    let query = this.db.select("*").from("users").where("username == " + username);
    let rows = this.db.exec(query);
    if (rows.count == 0) {
      throw "user not exists";
    }
    // Do the login
  }

  changePassword(username, newPassword, oldPassword) {
    let query = this.db.select("*").from("users").where("username == " + username);
    let rows = this.db.exec(query);
    if (rows.count == 0) {
      throw "user not exists";
    }
    // Do the password change
  }
}

As we can see, our AuthService class can be used to login users or to change their passwords. But we want to check whether the user exists before proceeding. So we include a pre-condition check in both methods.
There are seveeral reasons that makes this particularly not recommended.

We are making the same work twice. In the best case, we are copying and pasting the lines. But that's also an extra work to be considered.
The code is more difficult to read. More lines, and particularly repeated, reduces the focus on the really important things.
This is a source of errors. It's fragile. Let's note that we might need to change how the user existence is checked in the code. So we should do it in both methods. We run the risk of changing the code in one place only, leaving the other one as it was. This is a really subtle bug that could be unnoticed for a long time.

So refactoring the code as follows is recommended.
class AuthService {
  login(username, password) {
    this.checkUserExists(username);
    // Do the login
  }

  changePassword(username, newPassword, oldPassword) {
    this.checkUserExists(username);
    // Do the password change
  }

  checkUserExists(username) {
    let query = this.db.select("*").from("users").where("username == " + username);
    let rows = this.db.exec(query);
    if (rows.count == 0) {
      throw "user not exists";
    }
  }
}

You Aren't Gonna Need It (YAGNI)
Code is not for free. It has a cost. A cost to write it, and a cost to maintain it. So the more code you have, the more you are investing on it. As most of us write code to support some business, we expect to have a as much return of investment as possible from it. This has a special implication: each block of code we write has to add value to the software. Otherwise, it should not be written.
Too often, we write code we think it's useful. Or it will be useful in the future. Typically adding functionality to the application that is not really needed. The return of investment of that is negative. We dedicate time to write and maintain that code when actually is not producing value to the business.
The solution: do not write functionality that is not needed. Implement the most functionaly simple thing that could work. But note: this is not a declaration to do the code as fast as possible, implement hacks and forget about clean code, tests, etc. This is about functionality. Do not implement functionality that was not required.
Keep It Simple Stupid! (KISS)
Every piece in a machine is a possible source of failure. Every gear, bearing, switch, button, bulb, can fail by its own. And when they fail, it's really likely that the rest of the machine turns inoperative. Also, many pieces working together require a bigger cognitive load. These systems are more difficult to understand, to learn how they work.
It is a maths rule. The more pieces you have in your machine, the more probability of failure. And the more difficulties to understand how the machine work. Software is not an exception. An application comprised by hundred of modules working together is more error prone and hard to understand than one made of a bunch of them.
That's why keeping things simple and avoiding unnecessary complexity is a good practice.
The Billion Dollar Mistake
In 1965, Tony Hoare was working on the design of a new programming language: ALGOL W. This was the first language to incorporate the concept of reference: a type system artifact that make a variable to "point" to a value. They designed the language so references could be null, so they point to no value. Since then, almost every programming language that support references accepts null (some call it nil instead).
In 2009, Tony Hoare apologised for inventing the null reference during a conference in London. He called that his Billion Dollar Mistake. Null references has led to innumerable errors, vulnerabilities, and system crashes, which have probably caused a billion dollars of pain and damage since invented.
What's wrong with null references? Well, the main problem is that very often we programmers use to make an assumption over references: they are not null. We define a class, define some methods...
class ScanService {
  // ...
  scan(product, amount) {
    // ...
    this.total += product.price * amount;
    // ...
  }
}

...and we assume product and amount are never null. But then, somehow, a null value is received in product. Perhaps because it was read from a JSON field that came through a HTTP request. And we didn't check it is null or not while unmarshalling (again: we don't expect that). So we end up executing the equivalent to this.total += null.price * amount. And that fails throwing:
TypeError: Cannot read property 'price' of null
This happens all the time. It's the top 1 of mistakes that make a system crash. Probably the impact in the software industry is much more than 1 billion dollars.
How can we deal with this? Well, it's not easy. Unfortunately, most programming languages consider that any variable can be null (everything is a reference, thus everything can be null). That's the case of Javascript, Ruby, Python, Java... . Nevertheless, there are some useful tips that help to mitigate the effects.
The first one is to put barries in your code to prevent the entrance of null values in your application. If you receive data from the network, from a file, from a database, make sure it contains no null values. Implement validations there and do not let any null to enter your domains, signalling the error (throw an exception, return HTTP 400 response, etc).
Once we have that, we will find we have to admit a variable can be null. For example, the email field of our User data class could be null to indicate we don't have the email for that user. In these cases, it could be convenient to use a placeholder constant that represents that null value. The placeholder is not a null reference, but a reference to an actual value that can behave like a regular one.
var NULL_EMAIL = "Email address was not set";

class User {
  constructor(firstName, lastName) {
    this.firstName = firstName;
    this.lastName = lastName;
    this.email = NULL_EMAIL;
  }
}

Thanks to that, we will have a defined behavior for any possible value of email field, even when its null. For instance, we can print the User properties without checking if things are null or not, so using our favorite HTML renderer:
User information:

  First name: {{ $user.firstName }}
  Last name: {{ $user.lastName }}
  Email: {{ $user.email }}


We can also compare email values to check if they are unset when needed. For instance, while sending emails:
function mailing_campaign(users, message) {
  users.forEach(function (user) {
    if (user.email != NULL_EMAIL) {
      send_email(user.email, message);
    }
  })
}

Another way to solve this is to use an option type. This is a data type present in some languages that can have one of these two states:

Some(x), where x is the value it wraps. It represents a non-null value.
None. It represents a null value.

Some examples are the Optional generic class in Java 8 or the Option enum type in Rust.
The point is that, when using statically typed languages (read this section for more details), we will interact with the interface of that optional type, forcing the programmer to consider that it can be none.
class User {
  private String firstName;
  private String lastName;
  private Optional email;

  public User(String firstName, String lastName) {
    this.firstName = firstName;
    this.lastName = lastName;
    this.email = Optional.empty(); // This is None
  }

  public Optional getEmail() { return this.email; }

  public void setEmail(String value) {
    this.email = Optional.of(value); // This is Some(value)
  }
  // ...
}

User user = new User("John", "Carpenter");
user.setEmail("john.carpenter@example.com");

Our email property is not String, but Optional. So we have to use it accordingly:
void sendEmail(String address, String message) { ... }

void mailingCampaign(List users, String message) {
  for (User user : users) {
    // ERROR: getEmail() is not String but Optional
    // sendEmail(user.getEmail(), message)

    // OK: Optional implements ifPresent(), that will execute the action only when defined
    user.getEmail().ifPresent(email -> sendEmail(email, message));
  }
}

102-appendix-good-practices/99-polymorph.body:
Polymorphism and Abstract Types
If you come with a background in Javascript exclusively, it is very likely that terms like interface or abstract type are totally new to you. Since these terms are massivelly used when talking about good practices in Object Oriented Programming, we will dedicate this section to explain them in detail.
Dynamically vs statically typed languages
Javascript is a dynamically typed language. It roughtly means that the types of the variables of your program are determined in runtime, when the program is executed. One example in Javascript:
function isEven(num) {
  return num % 2 === 0;
}

Here, we expect num to be a number. But we do not indicate so in any way. We expect that, whenever this function is invoked when executed, the runtime will handle any possible type error. In Javascript, most of the situations are handled by doing nothing. In this particular case, passing anything that is not a number as argument will do: strings, objects, nulls... as all them respond to the % operator. So they will provide unexpected results. They will fail silently.
isEven(1) // false
isEven(2) // true
isEven("Hello") // false
isEven(null) // true
isEven(new Object) // false

Some other dynamically typed languages are more strict, and will throw an explicit error in this case.
def is_even(num)
  num % 2 == 0
end

is_even(1) # false
is_even(2) # true
is_even(nil) # NoMethodError: undefined method `%' for nil:NilClass
is_even(new Object) # NoMethodError: undefined method `new' for main:Object

These are dynamically typed languages. By contrast, some other are statically typed languages. Roughtly speaking, these languages are characterized by requiring the programmer to indicate what's the type of every variable used in his code. One example in Go:
func IsEven(num int) bool {
    return num % 2 == 0
}

As you can see, we have to indicate num is an integer value. We also indicate the result type of IsEven() function is a boolean. But, how is this information used? Simple. These languages have a compilation step prior to the execution of the program. While compiling, the source code is processed by a tool (the compiler) that will convert it in a "executable" program. In this conversion process, the program is also checked to be valid. And one of the validations the compiler do is a type check. It ensures IsEven(), and any other function, is not invoked with values of wrong data types. So this fragment of code would be accepted by the compiler:
  fmt.Println(IsEven(1)) // false
  fmt.Println(IsEven(2)) // true

While this other will not:
  fmt.Println(IsEven("Hello")) // compilation error: cannot use "Hello" (type string) as type int in argument to IsEven

Dynamically and statically typed languages implement abstractions in a different way. Thus, it's important to understand the difference before further discussion.
Polymorphism
This is a key concept related to abstractions in Object Oriented Programming. Polymorphism is the provision of a single interface to entities of different types. In other words, to define a contract of what we can obtain from an object (the interface) that is safisfied by different data types. Doing that we can write code that depends exclusively on the interface (what it does) and not in the implementation (how it does).
Polymorphism is implemented in a completely different way depending on the language is dynamically or statically typed. In dynamically typed languages, it is obtained via Duck Typing. Since type checks are done in runtime, the object is checked to implement a method call (implement the expected interface) when the program is executed. Some example in Javascript:
class Cat {
  talk() {
    return "Meow!";
  }
}

class Dog {
  talk() {
    return "Woof!";
  }
}

function f(animal) {
  console.log("The animal says: ", animal.talk());
}

Please note both classes, Cat and Dog, implement a talk() method. There is a really important implication here: both classes implement the same interface: an object that can respond to calls to talk(). We didn't specified the existence of such a interface in the code. But a kind of Animal interface is there, implicitely, in the code. This is essentially the Duck Typing: If it walks like a duck and it quacks like a duck, then it must be a duck. In other words, if we find in runtime a value that has the structure required by the interface, it works. In our example we could talk about animal typing. But... you get the idea.
In contrast, statically typed languages require that every type is specified before compilation. So in languages like Java we will use another technique: subtyping polymorphism.
interface Animal {
    abstract String talk();
}

class Cat implements Animal {
    String talk() {
        return "Meow!";
    }
}

class Dog implements Animal {
    String talk() {
        return "Woof!";
    }
}

void f(Animal a) {
  println(a.talk());
}

In this case, he had to declare the interface Animal explictly. We also indicated explicitely that both Cat and Dog implement the interface of Animal. And then we can define function f() to accept any value that implements the interface.
Abstractions
While talking about Object Oriented Design and good practices associated to it, we will mention things like interface, abstract class, implementation, etc. We are actually talking about using the polymorphism techniques available in our programming language to define interfaces for different types. And we will depict the things using diagrams like this one:

graph TD
  Animal-. implements .- Cat
  Animal-. implements .- Dog


So that's all about abstractions. Define interfaces, explicitely or not, that we can use in other parts of the code to abstract them from the actual implementations and separate the concerns.
